        <para id="id1164719549642"><emphasis effect="italics">Gain of an Amplifier:</emphasis> We will begin our discussion of decibels with an application in the field of electronics. An amplifier is an electronic device that is capable of boosting the power present in an input signal to produce an output signal with more power. It can be thought of as a black box as shown in Figure 1.</para>
        <figure id="id1164717087832"><media id="id1164717087832_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics1-1403.jpg" id="id1164717087832__onlineimage" height="238" width="319"/>
          </media>
        <caption>Block diagram of an amplifier.</caption></figure>
        <para id="id1164726582100">In practical cases, the ratio of the power in the output signal to the power in the input signal is a positive quantity whose value is greater than unity. The decibel measurement of this ratio of power is often called the <emphasis effect="italics">gain</emphasis> of the amplifier and is given as</para>
        
        <equation id="id1164734982064">
          <m:math>
            <m:semantics>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mstyle fontsize="12pt">
